{"type":"message","id":"ef2b2294","parentId":"26147291","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:34:59.360Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read_1771158899092_715","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"import sys\nimport os\nimport subprocess\nimport argparse\nimport signal\nimport time\nimport threading\n\nPID_FILE = \"src/bot.pid\"\nBOT_SCRIPT = \"src/trading_bot.py\"\nPROTOCOL_FILE = \"docs_archive/MASTER_PROTOCOL.md\"\n\ndef reload_protocol():\n    \"\"\"Reloads the master protocol configuration.\"\"\"\n    print(f\"[{time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}] Hot Reload: Active\")\n    # In a real implementation, this would signal the bot process or reload config\n    # For now, we just log as requested.\n\ndef monitor_protocol():\n    \"\"\"Monitors the protocol file for changes.\"\"\"\n    if not os.path.exists(PROTOCOL_FILE):\n        return\n\n    last_mtime = os.path.getmtime(PROTOCOL_FILE)\n    print(f\"[{time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}] Monitoring {PROTOCOL_FILE} for changes...\")\n\n    while True:\n        try:\n            current_mtime = os.path.getmtime(PROTOCOL_FILE)\n            if current_mtime != last_mtime:\n                last_mtime = current_mtime\n                reload_protocol()\n            time.sleep(1)\n        except OSError:\n            pass\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"Error monitoring protocol: {e}\")\n            time.sleep(5)\n\ndef start_monitor_thread():\n    \"\"\"Starts the monitor in a background thread.\"\"\"\n    monitor_thread = threading.Thread(target=monitor_protocol, daemon=True)\n    monitor_thread.start()\n\ndef is_running(pid):\n    \"\"\"Check if a process with the given PID is running.\"\"\"\n    try:\n        # Windows-specific check could be added here, but signal 0 is widely supported for existence check\n        # On Windows, os.kill with 0 is not supported in older versions, but usually fine in modern Python.\n        # Alternative: use tasklist\n        if os.name == 'nt':\n            # Use tasklist to check if PID exists\n            # Use errors='ignore' to handle potential non-UTF-8 output from localized Windows shell\n            output = subprocess.check_output(f'tasklist /FI \"PID eq {pid}\"', shell=True).decode(errors='ignore')\n            return str(pid) in output\n        else:\n            os.kill(pid, 0)\n            return True\n    except (OSError, subprocess.CalledProcessError):\n        return False\n\ndef start_bot():\n    if os.path.exists(PID_FILE):\n        with open(PID_FILE, 'r') as f:\n            try:\n                pid = int(f.read().strip())\n                if is_running(pid):\n                    print(f\"Bot is already running (PID: {pid}).\")\n                    return\n                else:\n                    print(\"Found stale PID file. Cleaning up.\")\n            except ValueError:\n                print(\"Invalid PID file. Cleaning up.\")\n        \n        os.remove(PID_FILE)\n\n    print(\"Starting bot...\")\n    # Detached execution\n    if os.name == 'nt':\n        # Windows: specific flags to detach\n        process = subprocess.Popen(\n            [sys.executable, BOT_SCRIPT],\n            creationflags=subprocess.CREATE_NEW_CONSOLE,\n            cwd=os.getcwd()\n        )\n    else:\n        # Unix\n        process = subprocess.Popen(\n            [sys.executable, BOT_SCRIPT],\n            stdout=subprocess.DEVNULL,\n            stderr=subprocess.DEVNULL,\n            stdin=subprocess.DEVNULL,\n            cwd=os.getcwd(),\n            start_new_session=True\n        )\n\n    with open(PID_FILE, 'w') as f:\n        f.write(str(process.pid))\n    \n    print(f\"Bot started with PID: {process.pid}\")\n\ndef stop_bot():\n    if not os.path.exists(PID_FILE):\n        print(\"Bot is not running (no PID file).\")\n        return\n\n    with open(PID_FILE, 'r') as f:\n        try:\n            pid = int(f.read().strip())\n        except ValueError:\n            print(\"Invalid PID file.\")\n            os.remove(PID_FILE)\n            return\n\n    if is_running(pid):\n        print(f\"Stopping bot (PID: {pid})...\")\n        try:\n            if os.name == 'nt':\n                subprocess.call(['taskkill', '/F', '/T', '/PID', str(pid)])\n            else:\n                os.kill(pid, signal.SIGTERM)\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"Error stopping bot: {e}\")\n    else:\n        print(\"Bot process not found. Cleaning up PID file.\")\n\n    if os.path.exists(PID_FILE):\n        os.remove(PID_FILE)\n    print(\"Bot stopped.\")\n\ndef status_bot():\n    if os.path.exists(PID_FILE):\n        with open(PID_FILE, 'r') as f:\n            content = f.read().strip()\n            # print(f\"DEBUG: Read '{content}'\")\n            try:\n                pid = int(content)\n                if is_running(pid):\n                    print(f\"STATUS: ACTIVE (PID: {pid})\")\n                    return\n                else:\n                    print(\"STATUS: INACTIVE (Stale PID file found)\")\n            except Exception as e:\n                print(f\"STATUS: ERROR (Corrupted PID file): {e}\")\n    else:\n        print(\"STATUS: INACTIVE\")\n\ndef main():\n    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description=\"Bot Control Interface\")\n    parser.add_argument('command', choices=['/start_bot', '/stop_bot', '/status', '/monitor'], help=\"Command to execute\")\n    \n    if len(sys.argv) < 2:\n        parser.print_help()\n        sys.exit(1)\n\n    args = parser.parse_args()\n\n    if args.command == '/start_bot':\n        start_bot()\n    elif args.command == '/stop_bot':\n        stop_bot()\n    elif args.command == '/status':\n        status_bot()\n    elif args.command == '/monitor':\n        print(f\"[{time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}] Starting protocol monitor...\")\n        monitor_protocol()\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1771158899358}}
{"type":"message","id":"8fd6c9a3","parentId":"ef2b2294","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:34:59.365Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read_1771158899204_716","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# MASTER PROTOCOL (Supreme Law)\n\n**Version:** 1.0.0  \n**Status:** ACTIVE  \n**Enforcement:** MANDATORY  \n**Authority:** PRO STREAM\n\n---\n\n## 1. PREAMBLE\nThis Master Protocol serves as the immutable \"Supreme Law\" for the OpenClaw Trading Automation System. All agents, sub-agents, and human operators must adhere to these directives. No code shall be deployed, no trade executed, and no system modified in violation of these tenets.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SACS-2026 (System Availability & Continuity Standard)\n**Objective:** Guarantee 99.99% uptime for core trading loops.\n\n*   **Fleet Integrity:** All 12 core agents (QUANT, NET, SENTINEL, OPS, DB, LOG, DMARKET, STEAM, HYPE, INVENTORY, SEC, LOGIC) must be active.\n*   **Heartbeat Protocol:** Every component must emit a heartbeat every 30 seconds. Three missed heartbeats trigger an automatic restart sequence.\n*   **Redundancy:** Critical paths (Price Feed, Order Execution) must have N+1 failover redundancy.\n\n## 3. ATOMIC ROLLBACK PROTOCOL\n**Objective:** Zero undefined states.\n\n*   **Definition:** Every deployment or configuration change is a transaction.\n*   **The Rule of Two:**\n    1.  **Pre-Flight Snapshot:** No change proceeds without a verified system snapshot.\n    2.  **Verification Gate:** Post-deployment validation must pass 100% of critical tests within 60 seconds.\n*   **Failure Response:** If Verification Gate fails, the system must *automatically* and *atomically* revert to the Pre-Flight Snapshot. No manual intervention required for safety restoration.\n\n## 4. SPEC-FIRST DEVELOPMENT\n**Objective:** Documentation leads implementation.\n\n*   **Workflow:**\n    1.  **Draft:** Create/Update the Markdown specification (e.g., `docs_archive/FEATURE.md`).\n    2.  **Review:** Validate the spec against the Master Protocol.\n    3.  **Code:** Implement strictly according to the approved spec.\n    4.  **Verify:** Tests must trace back to specific lines in the spec.\n*   **Prohibition:** \"Cowboy coding\" (implementation without documentation) is strictly forbidden.\n\n## 5. OBSERVABILITY & METRICS\n**Objective:** Total visibility, zero blind spots.\n\n*   **Logging:** JSON-structured logs are mandatory for all machine-readable events.\n*   **Metrics:**\n    *   **Latency:** Tracking of `tick-to-trade` latency at p50, p99, and p99.9.\n    *   **Error Rate:** Alert threshold at >1% error rate on any API interface.\n    *   **P&L:** Real-time tracking of Profit & Loss per strategy and aggregate.\n*   **Dashboards:** Monitoring states must be accessible via CLI (`/status`) and visual dashboards.\n\n## 6. HFT RULES (High-Frequency Trading)\n**Objective:** Speed with safety.\n\n*   **Risk Limits:**\n    *   **Max Drawdown:** Hard stop at 2% daily drawdown.\n    *   **Position Sizing:** No single position > 5% of total capital.\n    *   **Kill Switch:** A global hardware/software kill switch must be available to terminate all active orders in < 100ms.\n*   **Execution:**\n    *   **Maker/Taker:** Prefer Maker orders to capture rebate/spread unless high-urgency Taker liquidity is required.\n    *   **Inventory:** maintain neutral inventory exposure where possible (delta neutral strategies).\n\n---\n\n## 7. MODEL OPTIMIZATION STRATEGY\n**Objective:** Leverage AI model strengths for specific roles.\n\n### 7.1. Architect/Trader (Gemini 3 Pro)\n*   **Role:** Complex pattern recognition, strategy formulation, market analysis.\n*   **Context:** 1M+ token window for full historical price data analysis.\n*   **Configuration:**\n    *   `Temperature`: 0.7 (Balanced Creativity)\n    *   `Top_P`: 0.95\n*   **Usage:** Weekly strategy reviews, code architecture, anomaly investigation.\n\n### 7.2. Validator/Signal (Gemini 3 Flash)\n*   **Role:** High-speed syntax checking, trade signature validation, safety guardrails.\n*   **Configuration:**\n    *   `Temperature`: 0.0 (Strict Deterministic)\n    *   `Top_P`: 0.1\n*   **Usage:** Pre-trade checks, continuous integration pipelines, log parsing.\n\n## 8. SCALABLE MODELS\n**Objective:** Dynamic resource allocation based on task complexity.\n\n*   **Pro (Hourly Trend Analysis):**\n    *   Deep analysis of market depth and liquidity shifts.\n    *   Used for rebalancing portfolio weights and adjusting strategy parameters.\n*   **Flash (Per-Transaction Validation):**\n    *   Micro-second validation of order parameters.\n    *   Ensures compliance with HFT Rules (Section 6) before any signal leaves the boundary.\n\n---\n\n## 9. STRATEGY: FLOAT SNIPING & MARKET MAKING\n**Objective:** Capture inefficiencies in Float Value distribution.\n\n*   **Float Sniping:** Buy FT < 0.17 at market price. Sell at +15%.\n*   **Market Making:** Provide liquidity at spread > 2%.\n\n*Signed: SYSTEM ORCHESTRATOR*\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1771158899363}}
{"type":"message","id":"ff23fbf0","parentId":"8fd6c9a3","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:34:59.371Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read_1771158899333_717","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"import os\nimport sys\nimport subprocess\nimport logging\nimport asyncio\nfrom telegram import Update, BotCommand\nfrom telegram.ext import ApplicationBuilder, ContextTypes, CommandHandler\n\n# Configure logging\nlogging.basicConfig(\n    format='%(asctime)s - %(name)s - %(levelname)s - %(message)s',\n    level=logging.INFO\n)\n\n# Paths (Assuming run from workspace root)\nAGENT_WRAPPER = \"src/agent_wrapper.py\"\nPID_FILE = \"src/bot.pid\"\nMASTER_PROTOCOL = \"docs_archive/MASTER_PROTOCOL.md\"\nEVOLUTION_LOG = \"docs_archive/EVOLUTION_LOG.md\"\n\n# Token from Env\nTOKEN = os.getenv(\"TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN\")\n\nasync def dm_start(update: Update, context: ContextTypes.DEFAULT_TYPE):\n    \"\"\"🚀 Start DMarket HFT (High-Frequency)\"\"\"\n    await update.message.reply_text(\"🚀 Starting DMarket HFT Bot...\")\n    try:\n        # Run agent_wrapper from root\n        result = subprocess.run([sys.executable, AGENT_WRAPPER, \"/start_bot\"], capture_output=True, text=True)\n        \n        # Format output\n        output = result.stdout\n        if result.stderr:\n            output += \"\\nErrors:\\n\" + result.stderr\n            \n        await update.message.reply_text(f\"```\\n{output.strip()}\\n```\", parse_mode='Markdown')\n    except Exception as e:\n        await update.message.reply_text(f\"Failed to start bot: {e}\")\n\nasync def dm_stop(update: Update, context: ContextTypes.DEFAULT_TYPE):\n    \"\"\"🛑 EMERGENCY STOP & Flush\"\"\"\n    await update.message.reply_text(\"🛑 Stopping DMarket HFT Bot...\")\n    try:\n        result = subprocess.run([sys.executable, AGENT_WRAPPER, \"/stop_bot\"], capture_output=True, text=True)\n        \n        output = result.stdout\n        if result.stderr:\n            output += \"\\nErrors:\\n\" + result.stderr\n            \n        await update.message.reply_text(f\"```\\n{output.strip()}\\n```\", parse_mode='Markdown')\n    except Exception as e:\n        await update.message.reply_text(f\"Failed to stop bot: {e}\")\n\nasync def dm_status(update: Update, context: ContextTypes.DEFAULT_TYPE):\n    \"\"\"📊 Bot Health & Balance\"\"\"\n    status_msg = \"📊 **Bot Status Report**\\n\\n\"\n    \n    # 1. PID / Running State\n    if os.path.exists(PID_FILE):\n        try:\n            with open(PID_FILE, 'r') as f:\n                pid = f.read().strip()\n            status_msg += f\"✅ **Status:** Active (PID: {pid})\\n\"\n        except:\n            status_msg += \"⚠️ **Status:** PID file error\\n\"\n    else:\n        status_msg += \"💤 **Status:** Inactive (No PID file)\\n\"\n\n    # 2. Master Protocol Version\n    version = \"Unknown\"\n    if os.path.exists(MASTER_PROTOCOL):\n        try:\n            with open(MASTER_PROTOCOL, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:\n                # Look for Title or Version line\n                content = f.read()\n                lines = content.splitlines()\n                for line in lines:\n                    if \"Version\" in line or \"v.\" in line.lower():\n                        version = line.strip()\n                        break\n                if version == \"Unknown\" and lines:\n                     version = lines[0].strip()\n        except Exception as e:\n             version = f\"Error: {e}\"\n    status_msg += f\"📜 **Protocol:** {version}\\n\"\n\n    # 3. Evolution Log (Last Change)\n    last_change = \"None\"\n    if os.path.exists(EVOLUTION_LOG):\n        try:\n             with open(EVOLUTION_LOG, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:\n                lines = f.readlines()\n                # Get last non-empty line\n                for line in reversed(lines):\n                    if line.strip():\n                        last_change = line.strip()\n                        break\n        except:\n            pass\n    status_msg += f\"🧬 **Last Evolution:** {last_change}\\n\"\n    \n    # 4. LangFuse (Placeholder)\n    status_msg += \"🔎 **LangFuse Traces:** Active (Monitoring)\\n\"\n\n    await update.message.reply_text(status_msg, parse_mode='Markdown')\n\nasync def dm_dashboard(update: Update, context: ContextTypes.DEFAULT_TYPE):\n    \"\"\"📈 Open Control Panel\"\"\"\n    # Assuming local streamlit or configured URL\n    url = os.getenv(\"STREAMLIT_URL\", \"http://localhost:8501\")\n    await update.message.reply_text(f\"📈 **Control Panel:** [Open Dashboard]({url})\", parse_mode='Markdown')\n\nasync def post_init(application):\n    \"\"\"Set up commands on bot startup\"\"\"\n    commands = [\n        BotCommand(\"dm_start\", \"🚀 Start DMarket HFT\"),\n        BotCommand(\"dm_stop\", \"🛑 EMERGENCY STOP & Flush\"),\n        BotCommand(\"dm_status\", \"📊 Bot Health & Balance\"),\n        BotCommand(\"dm_dashboard\", \"📈 Open Control Panel\"),\n    ]\n    await application.bot.set_my_commands(commands)\n    logging.info(\"Commands registered with Telegram.\")\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    if not TOKEN:\n        print(\"Error: TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN not set. Please set it in your environment.\")\n        # For testing purposes, we might want to exit gracefully or mock it, \n        # but for a real deployment, we exit.\n        sys.exit(1)\n        \n    application = ApplicationBuilder().token(TOKEN).post_init(post_init).build()\n    \n    application.add_handler(CommandHandler('dm_start', dm_start))\n    application.add_handler(CommandHandler('dm_stop', dm_stop))\n    application.add_handler(CommandHandler('dm_status', dm_status))\n    application.add_handler(CommandHandler('dm_dashboard', dm_dashboard))\n    \n    print(\"Telegram Bot Control Interface Started.\")\n    application.run_polling()\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1771158899369}}
{"type":"message","id":"66473209","parentId":"ff23fbf0","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:35:12.368Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Evaluating Code Integration**\n\nI'm currently focused on integrating the code. Specifically, I'm examining `src/agent_wrapper.py`, `src/main.py`, and the `MASTER_PROTOCOL.md` documentation to understand how to proceed. My immediate task is to begin modifying `src/agent_wrapper.py`.\n\n\n**Analyzing Dependencies & Structure**\n\nI've examined the contents of `src/trading_bot.py`. It appears it *does* accept game arguments, which is excellent. Thus, I'm now proceeding with Step 1.2: modifying `src/agent_wrapper.py` to check for `fleet_mode` and spawn the appropriate workers. I'm currently structuring the process spawning logic. Next, I plan to create a basic `openclaw.json` for testing the `fleet_mode` implementation.\n\n\n**Reviewing Bot Argument Handling**\n\nI'm now reading `src/trading_bot.py` to determine how it handles command-line arguments. My aim is to confirm whether the trading bot accepts a `--game` argument, which is essential for launching it with specific game parameters. Once I verify this, I will move forward with modifying `src/agent_wrapper.py` to incorporate the fleet mode functionality.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"read_1771158912363_718","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"src/trading_bot.py"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":71382,"output":503,"cacheRead":68355,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":71885,"cost":{"input":0.142764,"output":0.0060360000000000006,"cacheRead":0.013671,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.162471}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771158899371}}
{"type":"message","id":"2fdd73a0","parentId":"66473209","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:35:12.388Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read_1771158912363_718","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"import time\nimport sys\nimport os\n\ndef main():\n    print(f\"[{time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}] BOT STARTED. PID: {os.getpid()}\")\n    sys.stdout.flush()\n    try:\n        while True:\n            print(f\"[{time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}] Bot running... monitoring markets.\")\n            sys.stdout.flush()\n            time.sleep(5)\n    except KeyboardInterrupt:\n        print(f\"[{time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}] BOT STOPPING...\")\n    except Exception as e:\n        print(f\"[{time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}] BOT CRASHED: {e}\")\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1771158912385}}
{"type":"message","id":"f5ed04fb","parentId":"2fdd73a0","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:35:19.907Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Contemplating Mode Implementation**\n\n\\n\\n\n\nI've begun outlining the implementation for fleet mode in `agent_wrapper.py`. My initial focus is on parsing `openclaw.json` to determine the fleet's configuration. The next step is to conditionally activate fleet logic based on the `fleet_mode` setting within that file. I'm considering the best way to integrate this new functionality with the existing game argument parsing, which needs to accommodate the new fleet-specific parameters.\n\n\n**Drafting Configuration Schema**\n\n\\n\\n\n\nI've decided to start by crafting the `openclaw.json` file to establish the parameters for fleet mode operation. It will include a `fleet_mode` boolean and a `system_capabilities` object detailing features such as batch execution, lazy loading, and checkpointing.  Then I will update `src/trading_bot.py` to handle the new game arguments. Finally, I will write the logic for spawning workers, based on the `fleet_mode` setting, and saving their PIDs.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"write_1771158919898_719","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"{\n  \"fleet_mode\": true,\n  \"system_capabilities\": {\n    \"batch_execution\": true,\n    \"lazy_loading\": true,\n    \"checkpoints\": true\n  }\n}","file_path":"openclaw.json"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":71860,"output":359,"cacheRead":68131,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":72219,"cost":{"input":0.14372,"output":0.004308,"cacheRead":0.013626200000000002,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.1616542}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771158912389}}
