{"type":"message","id":"1c0c97ec","parentId":"61195d02","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:36:16.028Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Developing the Demo Script**\n\nI'm now focusing on creating the batch task demo script, specifically `src/batch_task.py`. The aim is to simulate parallel data fetching using threading, taking a list of games as input. I'm considering how to best structure the data fetching logic to maximize efficiency.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"write_1771158976022_724","name":"write","arguments":{"file_path":"src/batch_task.py","content":"import threading\nimport time\nimport random\n\ndef scan_target(game):\n    print(f\"[BATCH] Scanning {game} targets...\")\n    delay = random.uniform(0.5, 2.0)\n    time.sleep(delay)\n    items = random.randint(10, 50)\n    print(f\"[BATCH] {game}: Found {items} items (Time: {delay:.2f}s)\")\n\ndef main():\n    print(\"[BATCH] Starting parallel scan...\")\n    games = [\"CS2\", \"Rust\", \"TF2\"]\n    threads = []\n    \n    start_time = time.time()\n    \n    for game in games:\n        t = threading.Thread(target=scan_target, args=(game,))\n        threads.append(t)\n        t.start()\n        \n    for t in threads:\n        t.join()\n        \n    print(f\"[BATCH] Scan complete in {time.time() - start_time:.2f}s\")\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":75780,"output":299,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":76079,"cost":{"input":0.15156,"output":0.003588,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.155148}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771158968122}}
